WEBVTT

00:00.290 --> 00:02.773
Well, good morning, Menlo Church, welcome.

00:03.113 --> 00:04.434
So glad that you are here.

00:04.454 --> 00:14.565
Be honest with me though, how many of you, when you saw that we were doing a series on love in the month of February, like internally, just a little bit, you had like an eye roll about it.

00:15.647 --> 00:16.407
It's fine, I get it.

00:17.028 --> 00:25.477
We are one day into February, which means for the next couple of weeks, you are going to be inundated by Hallmark Target Instagram.

00:25.517 --> 00:30.002
Everywhere you go, everywhere you look, we're gonna be inundated with talk about

00:30.210 --> 00:30.591
Love.

00:30.651 --> 00:38.384
And 99% of what we're going to be inundated about is mushy, cheap, and honestly not that helpful.

00:38.464 --> 00:45.797
It's either dating advice you've heard a thousand times or it's a cliche that probably leaves you more lonely than inspired.

00:46.218 --> 00:48.702
So I want to address that before we get started today.

00:48.802 --> 00:52.268
We are not giving a dating sermon for some of you.

00:52.288 --> 00:53.831
You're like, that's why I showed up.

00:53.851 --> 00:55.474
Hopefully it'll still be helpful.

00:55.554 --> 00:59.100
If you're single, you're not gonna get a checklist of finding a spouse.

00:59.180 --> 01:03.146
If you're married, we are not gonna give five tips to spice things up.

01:03.186 --> 01:05.590
You can talk about that with somebody over donuts afterwards.

01:06.291 --> 01:15.045
The elephant in the room is that really what we're gonna spend time today and in this series talking about is the single most important word in the English language.

01:15.085 --> 01:21.515
And most of us deep down, whether you're a person of faith or not, feel like we have gotten this word and this concept wrong.

01:21.716 --> 01:23.218
We are exhausted.

01:23.298 --> 01:27.186
by the cultural chaos that surrounds the idea of love.

01:27.226 --> 01:31.115
We're tired of the confusion, the commitment phobia, the broken definitions.

01:31.175 --> 01:35.364
The question for us today is not how do I find love, but really it's more foundational.

01:35.384 --> 01:38.450
It starts with, what is it in the first place?

01:38.722 --> 01:45.068
And if you're someone wondering how we approach, you saw a series like this, you're like, how do you think about gender and sexuality?

01:45.108 --> 01:47.331
How do you guys talk about that or approach that?

01:47.411 --> 01:58.322
We did an extensive series with messages and additional resources in partnership with other churches called Wonderfully Made that you can find and check out at menlo.church.connect.

01:58.822 --> 02:03.327
But before we dive any further into this series around this concept, I'm gonna pray for us.

02:03.507 --> 02:06.290
And if you've never been here before or never heard me speak,

02:06.370 --> 02:23.371
Before I speak, I pray kneeling and part of the reason that I do that on a day like today and for a series like this one is because I know that folks up in San Mateo, down in Saratoga, in Mountain View, here in Menlo Park, people online all around the world, the idea of love for a lot of us brings up a lot of pain.

02:23.791 --> 02:31.501
And so what I hope we'll get a chance to do is wherever we've built walls, God might bring those walls down, might soften our hearts to learn from Him today.

02:32.142 --> 02:33.844
So what did you pray with me that you might do that now?

02:34.785 --> 02:35.666
God, thank you.

02:36.386 --> 02:39.170
that your love for us really is inexhaustible.

02:39.210 --> 02:41.873
It's not just what you do, it's who you are.

02:42.494 --> 02:54.530
And so right now for any of us that are skeptical of that, for any of us that have put walls up, for any of us that are thinking about a litmus test, we're gonna apply to this idea, would you help us to just hear from you?

02:55.151 --> 03:01.719
Even beyond the words that I have to say or the concepts we might share that they would have an encounter with you in these moments.

03:01.739 --> 03:03.762
In Jesus' name, amen.

03:04.706 --> 03:17.644
Now, if I asked you with this series idea, love is, if I asked you to answer this question, love is and fill in your answer, what might you put right here?

03:18.245 --> 03:21.129
See, for some people, love is fun.

03:21.470 --> 03:23.112
Love is easy.

03:23.212 --> 03:26.637
For some people like my wife, she would say love is popcorn.

03:26.657 --> 03:29.441
Like she really likes popcorn a lot.

03:29.461 --> 03:31.504
For some of you, love is Instagram.

03:31.544 --> 03:32.946
You're a big fan of it.

03:33.026 --> 03:37.031
whatever your current thing is that you're scrolling instead of listening.

03:37.491 --> 03:40.274
For some of you, love is like a spark, right?

03:40.294 --> 03:47.202
You think to yourself, oh, it's that instant feeling of attraction to someone or romantically someone that's your soulmate.

03:47.482 --> 03:51.867
The way you would think about love is one of these ideas.

03:52.508 --> 03:55.812
And really culturally, that's part of the problem.

03:56.172 --> 04:01.298
As a matter of fact, for most of us, love is basically vibes.

04:01.506 --> 04:06.552
It is the feelings that we have in the moment that determines the choices that we make.

04:07.073 --> 04:08.154
It's about chemistry.

04:08.435 --> 04:11.078
It's about the ick that instantly kills the vibe.

04:11.578 --> 04:12.259
Oh, or the spark.

04:12.299 --> 04:13.361
That's the first time that's happened.

04:13.401 --> 04:16.545
The spark that lifts the vibe is all planned.

04:17.726 --> 04:22.191
For those of you, by the way, who are over 40, and I just said the word ick, and you're like, I've heard that.

04:22.372 --> 04:23.273
What does that mean?

04:23.293 --> 04:27.538
And ick is a strangely specific thing

04:27.618 --> 04:30.342
that makes you instantly lose attraction to someone.

04:30.382 --> 04:32.565
You're like, I didn't know that word, but I know that feeling.

04:33.366 --> 04:34.628
It's not a moral failure.

04:34.868 --> 04:37.792
It's stuff like wearing socks with sandals.

04:40.236 --> 04:43.019
It's like the moment when somebody claps when the plane lands.

04:44.582 --> 04:45.303
Ick, right?

04:45.743 --> 04:50.290
It's when somebody runs with a backpack, but like the backpack bounces too much, right?

04:50.870 --> 04:56.338
It sounds ridiculous, but in a vibes culture, a bouncy backpack is grounds for a breakup.

04:56.866 --> 04:58.829
That's the thing that we think about love today.

04:58.909 --> 05:05.998
Love has become something that we fall into like a ditch or something we fall out of like a tree.

05:06.058 --> 05:08.902
And the problem with that should be clear, right?

05:08.942 --> 05:26.546
If love is just a feeling, if it's just vibes, then the moment that the feeling fades, the love leaves, the romantic relationship, the close friendship, the circle of friends, even family relationships, where we can have our feelings change instantly, we let the relationship change.

05:26.818 --> 05:27.979
to follow.

05:27.999 --> 05:32.845
Now, what if love is less decoration and more foundation?

05:32.925 --> 05:34.827
That's the question I want you to think about today.

05:35.648 --> 05:38.611
This year, our family, we're having our house remodel.

05:38.631 --> 05:40.433
It's not really our house, it's owned by a foundation.

05:40.453 --> 05:41.494
We're really grateful for that.

05:42.175 --> 05:56.050
But throughout the planning process of thinking about this remodel, there's work that we've had to do to be able to figure out what we wanted to change, what really could change, because it was decorative, and the stuff that we couldn't change, because it actually supported the house.

05:56.386 --> 06:01.351
Now, if we are not careful, we basically treat love like interior design for our lives.

06:02.012 --> 06:06.677
It's there to make our lives look pretty, to feel cozy, to match our aesthetic, our vibe.

06:06.737 --> 06:11.282
When the style changes, though, when our feelings change, we renovate.

06:11.322 --> 06:15.487
We break up, we freeze someone out, we find a new friend, or maybe even a new friend group.

06:16.408 --> 06:20.793
But in God's blueprints, love isn't the paint, it's the beams.

06:21.293 --> 06:25.458
You don't always see the beams, you don't understand necessarily what's behind that wall.

06:25.570 --> 06:32.723
They aren't always the most attractive, but if you remove them because you're bored with them, the roof will cave in on your head.

06:33.224 --> 06:38.754
It will happen if you're doing a renovation of your house and it will happen if you think about love overly simplistically.

06:38.814 --> 06:41.719
Love isn't something that just makes life look good.

06:41.959 --> 06:45.205
It's something that keeps our life from collapsing.

06:45.886 --> 06:50.194
So to better understand that, we need the biblical definition of love.

06:50.690 --> 06:54.555
Love is a topic that the Bible addresses consistently through its pages.

06:54.996 --> 06:59.382
God's definition appears in a couple of places that we're gonna look at today.

06:59.442 --> 07:04.449
And the first place comes from a letter in the New Testament of your Bible called First John.

07:04.549 --> 07:12.960
Now it's First John because there are multiple letters that John writes and it's really clear by necessity.

07:13.241 --> 07:20.050
When you learn Greek, the language that this was originally written in your first semester studying Greek, you study

07:20.194 --> 07:26.041
John because John was so clear and the reason he was so clear was a necessity.

07:26.101 --> 07:28.824
He did not have a strong grasp of grammar in Greek.

07:28.844 --> 07:33.710
He did not have an extensive Greek vocabulary which as a first-year Greek student you're like me either.

07:33.770 --> 07:36.814
We're friends and so it makes it easier to translate.

07:37.194 --> 07:41.620
And so in first John chapter 4 we see this breakdown.

07:41.660 --> 07:43.442
It says beloved let us

07:43.586 --> 07:44.867
Love one another.

07:44.988 --> 07:46.850
Pay attention to how many times he talks about love.

07:46.890 --> 07:53.137
For love is from God and whoever loves has been born of God and who knows God.

07:53.237 --> 07:55.880
Anyone who does not love does not know God.

07:56.220 --> 07:59.924
And then here's this line, because God is love.

08:00.044 --> 08:08.273
Now this passage right here, actually at 16 years old, the very first sermon that I ever preached on a Sunday morning to a church was this passage.

08:08.674 --> 08:12.658
And if you're like, how'd that sermon turn out terribly?

08:13.026 --> 08:14.909
So today will be better, I'm sure of it.

08:14.949 --> 08:19.736
He continues, in this, the love of God was made manifest among us that God sent his only son.

08:19.776 --> 08:23.201
If you wanna know what love is, John says, here's what love is.

08:23.541 --> 08:28.788
God sent his only son into the world so that we might live through him.

08:29.149 --> 08:37.220
In this is love, not that we have loved God, but that he has loved us and sent his son to be the propitiation.

08:37.241 --> 08:38.763
This is the only big word he gives us.

08:39.183 --> 08:41.106
It just means to take our place

08:41.378 --> 08:47.270
The thing you and I deserved, he took even though he didn't and then he finishes our passage this way.

08:47.571 --> 08:53.283
He says, beloved, if God so loved us, we also ought to love one another.

08:53.303 --> 08:56.830
No one has ever seen God if we love one another, God abides.

08:56.870 --> 09:00.818
He stays in us and his love is perfected.

09:01.602 --> 09:01.982
in us.

09:02.043 --> 09:07.449
I told you that for John, this idea of staying simple, God and love.

09:07.469 --> 09:18.122
If you know those two basic Greek words, I could teach them to you right now, you will have a very, very basic idea, but very clear idea of what John's trying to communicate.

09:18.482 --> 09:24.069
When we think about this, we get a snapshot from John about what it is he's trying to communicate to me.

09:24.089 --> 09:25.371
Don't miss this though.

09:25.711 --> 09:28.274
His translation is very simple.

09:28.674 --> 09:35.043
But what often happens in the New Testament is something is very simple as a means of removing the loopholes.

09:35.504 --> 09:37.567
When it's really simple, there's no place to hide.

09:37.627 --> 09:39.669
It becomes more demanding.

09:40.350 --> 09:43.555
Our culture says that love is God.

09:44.216 --> 09:49.924
Meaning that whatever I feel deeply, whatever desire I have right now, that is what's ultimate for me.

09:50.224 --> 09:52.007
That actually is my God.

09:52.407 --> 09:55.332
If it feels like love, it must be right.

09:55.392 --> 09:57.074
That's vibes, right?

09:57.762 --> 10:02.910
But John, who Jesus took a chance on, wasn't born a saint.

10:02.970 --> 10:08.939
As a matter of fact, if you met John when he was young, you probably wouldn't think this is a guy that is very loving.

10:09.039 --> 10:10.882
You'd probably think he was dangerous.

10:11.483 --> 10:15.709
Remember, Jesus, he didn't give John a cute nickname like the peacemaker.

10:16.310 --> 10:21.778
In Mark chapter three, Jesus snakes the names John and his brother James, the sons of thunder.

10:21.798 --> 10:24.242
I know it sounds like a killer 80s band.

10:24.898 --> 10:29.844
But the reason that they were given that name is because they had explosive tempers.

10:30.445 --> 10:44.662
This is the guy actually in Luke 9, when a Samaritan asked, or when a Samaritan village wouldn't welcome Jesus, John turned to Jesus and asked him, hey Lord, do you want me to call down fire from heaven to destroy them?

10:45.363 --> 10:47.946
Like have you been hanging out with Jesus for more than five minutes?

10:48.186 --> 10:49.548
He does not want you to do that.

10:50.209 --> 10:54.354
His response to rejection wasn't love his patient, love his kind,

10:54.690 --> 10:57.013
His response was, love is napalm.

10:57.033 --> 10:58.534
Let's burn everything down.

10:58.594 --> 11:00.477
He was reactionary.

11:00.517 --> 11:01.738
He was judgmental.

11:02.018 --> 11:07.004
He was the original vision of cancel culture, except he wasn't trying to kill your social media account.

11:07.044 --> 11:10.087
He was trying to cancel your zip code.

11:10.107 --> 11:12.850
So you're thinking, yeah, you're kind of undercutting the message.

11:13.771 --> 11:15.233
So why does his perspective matter?

11:15.954 --> 11:18.917
Why should we listen to the fire from heaven guy teach us about love?

11:19.758 --> 11:23.122
Because first John wasn't written by the young

11:23.266 --> 11:24.928
hot-headed son of thunder.

11:24.948 --> 11:32.659
It was written by the old man who spent a lifetime being softened by the grace of Jesus.

11:33.180 --> 11:41.511
He is writing this letter decades later, likely as the last surviving apostle after the others were murdered for their faith.

11:42.212 --> 11:44.896
He's seen empires rise and empires fall.

11:45.116 --> 11:48.341
He has seen cultural definitions of love come and go.

11:48.681 --> 11:51.986
And looking back on all of it, the man who

11:52.258 --> 11:56.847
Used to demand fire is now declaring fellowship and friendship.

11:57.909 --> 12:08.309
See, when this guy, the one who wanted to nuke his enemies tells you and me that God is love, he isn't writing a greeting card for you're in my Valentine's card later this month.

12:08.569 --> 12:15.282
He is telling you and me the only force in the universe strong enough to change a heart like his is God's.

12:15.714 --> 12:18.500
He's saying, I know what the human heart looks like.

12:18.800 --> 12:19.922
It looks like reaction.

12:19.982 --> 12:21.145
It looks like revenge.

12:21.265 --> 12:22.427
It looks like outrage.

12:22.668 --> 12:26.495
But let me tell you what I have learned from the one who loved me when I was unlovable.

12:27.417 --> 12:28.800
That gives him credibility.

12:29.581 --> 12:32.347
He's not writing about a theory we should think about.

12:32.908 --> 12:35.954
He's writing about his own transformation.

12:36.514 --> 12:39.258
See, culture might say that love is God and to find it.

12:39.559 --> 12:48.312
However, they see fit in the moment, but God says that for you and me, God is himself the definition of love.

12:48.913 --> 12:51.857
It's the foundation of everything in our lives.

12:52.158 --> 12:54.842
It's actually the foundation of existence itself.

12:55.663 --> 13:05.778
And even with John's limited vocabulary, he uses a word for love in Greek that is really important because it's impossible for us to do on our own.

13:06.146 --> 13:11.331
There are multiple words in the Bible that we translate as love, which is part of the problem.

13:11.371 --> 13:14.814
That's why we can love popcorn and Instagram and love our spouse.

13:15.275 --> 13:17.877
We don't mean the same thing, but it's the only word that we have.

13:18.438 --> 13:25.445
But one of those words in Greek actually is the most divine and the most demanding of all of them.

13:25.485 --> 13:26.526
It's the word agape.

13:26.986 --> 13:30.069
And that's the one that John uses over and over and over again.

13:30.650 --> 13:34.994
It points to a self-giving, self-sacrificial vision of love.

13:35.458 --> 13:39.186
A vision of love that isn't decoration, it's foundation.

13:40.008 --> 13:50.770
When John says, in this is love, not that we have loved God, but that He loved us and sent His Son into the world so that we might live through Him.

13:51.234 --> 13:55.059
He's showing us that real love isn't about you and me reaching God.

13:55.079 --> 13:58.024
That's what every other religion outside of biblical Christianity does.

13:58.364 --> 14:00.327
Here's the latter, you climb to get to God.

14:00.367 --> 14:00.848
No, no, no.

14:01.128 --> 14:07.317
What John is saying is Jesus is the only time that God climbed down to get to us.

14:07.457 --> 14:08.879
That's the good news of the gospel.

14:09.620 --> 14:17.631
Agape love is a self-sacrificing choice to seek the highest good of another, regardless of how they respond.

14:18.733 --> 14:19.474
I promise.

14:19.874 --> 14:24.100
If love was just vibes, Jesus would never have hung on the cross for you.

14:25.141 --> 14:30.950
He chose to do it because of the true nature of love, his true nature.

14:31.771 --> 14:35.917
And this is where we kind of hit the hardest tension for our culture today.

14:36.678 --> 14:45.490
In his book, The Rise and Triumph of the Modern Self, the historian Carl Truman, he diagnoses why the biblical definition feels so foreign to us today.

14:45.762 --> 14:52.231
He argues that we have shifted into an era that he describes as expressive individualism.

14:52.351 --> 14:57.579
Basically, for most of human history, people looked externally to define reality.

14:57.599 --> 14:59.081
They looked outside of themselves.

14:59.101 --> 15:01.985
They looked to God, they looked to community, they looked to a moral code.

15:02.266 --> 15:05.350
But today, we are told to look inward.

15:05.730 --> 15:11.859
We are taught that the real me lies within my own feelings, desires, and experiences.

15:12.480 --> 15:13.842
And under that worldview,

15:14.146 --> 15:18.555
The greatest sin that you can commit is to be inauthentic.

15:20.879 --> 15:24.045
If I feel it inside, I must express it on the outside.

15:24.606 --> 15:26.069
Or else I'm living a lie.

15:26.109 --> 15:29.776
Do you see why that's made our definition of love feel so fragile?

15:30.017 --> 15:32.722
Maybe that's why it's made us sometimes so fragile.

15:33.250 --> 15:45.945
If my inner feelings are the ultimate authority, if love is God, then the moment that my feelings for you change, I have a moral obligation in expressive individualism to leave you.

15:46.866 --> 15:52.233
If the vibe shifts, I have to bail because to stay would be fake.

15:53.214 --> 15:56.818
Truman points out that this has left us incredibly lonely.

15:57.154 --> 16:05.469
both personally and collectively, because when you make your inner feelings the foundation of your life, you are building on a foundation that shifts every single day.

16:05.810 --> 16:08.595
You become a slave to your own moods and experiences.

16:08.615 --> 16:11.500
As a matter of fact, in church history, there's a framework for this.

16:11.920 --> 16:15.026
It's called a Wesley and Quadrilateral, and it has four sides.

16:15.074 --> 16:29.035
And the idea is that the foundation of our decision-making would be the scriptures, the way that God tells us the world works, then above that the traditions of how humans have worked out that wisdom in their life, then above that our logic, then above that our emotions.

16:29.455 --> 16:34.943
The foundation is the most important and we get to the least important, still necessary, but not the most important.

16:35.564 --> 16:37.948
If you're paying attention, we live in a culture that's flipped them.

16:38.709 --> 16:41.633
Your emotions, your experience has become primary.

16:42.635 --> 16:44.818
But John, he offers us a better way.

16:45.282 --> 16:50.428
By saying, God is love, He's inviting us to take the weight off of our own unstable emotions.

16:51.049 --> 16:56.215
He is saying, stop looking at yourself to find your definition of love and look at the cross instead.

16:57.157 --> 17:02.843
Speaking of looking at things, some of you have been looking up here and you're like, Phil, do you know that there is an anchor and a balloon behind you?

17:04.405 --> 17:05.126
I just figured it out.

17:05.206 --> 17:05.887
No, I knew it was here.

17:06.848 --> 17:11.274
And this balloon really demonstrates something for you and me today.

17:11.334 --> 17:14.738
It demonstrates the choice that we have about the kind of love

17:15.202 --> 17:16.083
that we want to pursue.

17:16.123 --> 17:26.019
We can float away with our feelings in this state that is fragile like the balloon with layers of love that are kind of like this inflated latex balloon.

17:26.940 --> 17:33.871
We can find ourselves with a very thin layer that's very fragile and something that can leak out of it and dissipate over time.

17:34.492 --> 17:43.346
Or we can connect to the unchanging nature and person of God himself, his character, his love for you and me that doesn't float around.

17:44.130 --> 17:48.216
When we look inward, we find a balloon that floats with our feelings.

17:48.757 --> 17:54.125
But when we look at Jesus, we find an anchor that holds through the storm.

17:55.167 --> 17:58.151
Love isn't about just expressing what you feel.

17:59.073 --> 18:03.079
It's about anchoring yourself in who God actually is.

18:03.139 --> 18:08.086
Now, I wanna address an extreme that this can lead to.

18:08.867 --> 18:10.690
I'm not saying that your feelings don't matter.

18:10.810 --> 18:11.632
Your feelings matter.

18:11.772 --> 18:13.234
It's not even that your feelings are

18:13.442 --> 18:14.123
inaccurate.

18:14.643 --> 18:19.308
It's just that they are inadequate to be the primary tool you use to steer your life.

18:19.948 --> 18:26.375
I've heard it put this way, that if your life is a vehicle, your feelings should have a seat in the car of your life.

18:26.575 --> 18:28.156
Just make sure it's not the driver's seat.

18:28.977 --> 18:31.419
And some of you have had your feelings minimized for a long time.

18:31.860 --> 18:32.861
Feel your feelings.

18:32.921 --> 18:35.123
Just don't let your feelings steer your life.

18:36.464 --> 18:42.290
So if the balloon is our feelings and this anchor is God's character, we need to know who God is.

18:42.946 --> 18:44.888
And that brings us to 1 Corinthians 13.

18:45.870 --> 18:50.055
Even if you're not a Christian, you've probably heard some of the verses from 1 Corinthians 13.

18:50.235 --> 18:51.477
We use them like a to-do list.

18:51.817 --> 18:55.302
We say be patient, be kind, don't be jealous.

18:56.203 --> 18:59.527
This idea that like, all right, there's some pretty high standards.

18:59.567 --> 19:06.095
And before I've even finished reading the definition of love in 1 Corinthians 13, I feel guilty because I've failed hit.

19:07.137 --> 19:11.282
But if John is right, if God is love,

19:11.906 --> 19:14.689
then 1 Corinthians 13 isn't just some set of rules.

19:15.750 --> 19:16.731
It's a biography.

19:17.872 --> 19:20.374
It's a description of the anchor of God's love.

19:21.115 --> 19:25.059
It is the portrait of the God who holds you and me.

19:25.479 --> 19:29.923
So when we read this, we don't just hear this as a command for us to live out.

19:30.824 --> 19:33.687
We hear it as a description, a portrait of God's love for us.

19:34.408 --> 19:37.171
Because you cannot emulate what you have not experienced.

19:37.771 --> 19:40.754
Some of you, you have heard a message like this

19:40.962 --> 19:50.953
You have heard the idea of what God wants you to do in your life and the challenge and pain for you is you've never actually experienced this love from God in your life.

19:51.834 --> 19:53.055
Man, that can change today.

19:53.916 --> 20:02.845
Too often we read these words at weddings and the thing is like we realize very quickly in marriage that we are incapable of living them out perfectly, right?

20:03.586 --> 20:07.250
But if you know the context, Paul did not write these so that

20:07.842 --> 20:08.943
weddings could use them.

20:09.003 --> 20:14.270
Paul wrote these to a specific church in the first century that was fighting with each other.

20:14.310 --> 20:15.411
They were suing each other.

20:15.431 --> 20:16.793
They were obsessed with status.

20:17.093 --> 20:22.640
They were making the kinds of assumptions and labels of one another that feel very familiar to us today.

20:22.660 --> 20:25.503
1 Corinthians is actually a rebuke.

20:25.643 --> 20:27.545
It's a letter of correction.

20:27.986 --> 20:30.949
And so when we jump into it, Paul says these words.

20:31.911 --> 20:33.512
Love is patient.

20:33.973 --> 20:34.834
Love is kind.

20:35.234 --> 20:36.676
Love does not envy or boast.

20:36.756 --> 20:38.037
It's not arrogant or rude.

20:38.598 --> 20:40.800
It does not insist on its own way.

20:40.860 --> 20:42.962
It's not irritable or resentful.

20:43.643 --> 20:47.367
It does not rejoice at wrongdoing, but it actually rejoices with the truth.

20:47.447 --> 20:53.634
Love bears all things, believes all things, hopes all things, endures all things.

20:53.694 --> 21:01.042
Now, I just want you to know, I actually took like seven years of formal education

21:01.250 --> 21:03.654
in biblical Greek and biblical Hebrews.

21:03.674 --> 21:04.916
I want to give you a little bit of shortcut.

21:05.276 --> 21:07.479
This comes from a word, pass upon in Greek.

21:08.381 --> 21:09.683
Let me just give you a quick shortcut.

21:09.703 --> 21:10.825
Do you know what it means in Greek?

21:12.107 --> 21:12.647
It means all.

21:15.071 --> 21:16.734
I just want to save you a step.

21:17.895 --> 21:30.194
And so what he gives us for the snapshot of this is a snapshot of what it means for you and me to experience love not as a list of to-do's that we can't do, but a list of characters

21:30.402 --> 21:33.947
that God embodies in every moment of our day.

21:33.967 --> 21:36.631
Do you see this vision of agape?

21:37.012 --> 21:39.976
It requires God to model it in us.

21:40.257 --> 21:43.281
It requires God to motivate us, to activate in us.

21:43.321 --> 21:45.124
We are helpless to do this on our own.

21:45.585 --> 21:46.626
So you have to go back to our question.

21:46.646 --> 21:49.310
What if love is less decoration and more foundation?

21:50.672 --> 21:51.614
Love is patient.

21:52.355 --> 21:54.398
What if you don't feel patient?

21:55.279 --> 21:56.521
What if you feel annoyed?

21:57.703 --> 21:59.826
Love is the choice in the moment to wait

22:00.066 --> 22:03.810
when you want to rush, to defer rather than always getting what you prefer.

22:04.171 --> 22:04.851
Love is kind.

22:05.712 --> 22:13.021
Kindness isn't just being nice, it's being useful, it's being helpful, it's serving someone, sometimes, even when that person drains you to serve.

22:13.041 --> 22:16.825
I mean, that never happens to me, but I've heard from some of you that it happens in your life.

22:16.845 --> 22:18.427
Love keeps no record of wrongs.

22:18.447 --> 22:19.928
Well, are you kidding me?

22:21.070 --> 22:22.551
What about the last time they did that thing?

22:22.571 --> 22:25.234
What about the next time that they're definitely gonna do that thing?

22:25.274 --> 22:28.658
See, our feelings, they keep a detailed ledger.

22:29.378 --> 22:32.462
But love, love shreds the receipt.

22:33.803 --> 22:47.499
Now, I need to hit pause for just a second because anytime I do this, whenever we talk about love enduring all things, keeping no record of wrongs, there is someone who is going to hear that as a command to stay in a dangerous or abusive situation.

22:47.559 --> 22:48.641
Let me be crystal clear.

22:50.102 --> 22:52.765
The idea of love in the Bible is not a doormat.

22:53.566 --> 22:55.449
If you aren't safe, get safe.

22:55.489 --> 22:56.690
Talk to someone today.

22:57.026 --> 22:58.267
get out of that situation.

22:58.327 --> 22:59.268
Love actually protects.

22:59.969 --> 23:08.037
And sometimes the most loving thing that you can do for someone is to set a boundary that makes it impossible for them to sin against you or hurt you again.

23:09.318 --> 23:12.481
See, enduring does not mean staying silent in the midst of it.

23:12.922 --> 23:14.804
It means seeking safety from it.

23:15.845 --> 23:21.470
But for the vast majority of us, we aren't dealing with abuse.

23:22.552 --> 23:25.074
We're dealing with annoyance.

23:25.890 --> 23:27.453
We aren't dealing with safety.

23:28.074 --> 23:29.617
We are dealing with our own selfishness.

23:30.358 --> 23:34.385
Don't use the exception of abuse as an excuse for a lack of grace in your life.

23:35.387 --> 23:38.553
Most of us, we aren't setting boundaries because we're in danger.

23:38.673 --> 23:42.340
We're building walls because we're proud and we don't want to deal with those areas of our life.

23:43.302 --> 23:50.034
If you're trying to figure out the difference between a difficult relationship that needs grace and a destructive relationship that needs space,

23:50.242 --> 23:52.570
I want to recommend a book that I've recommended many times.

23:53.272 --> 23:56.242
It's a book called Boundaries by Henry Cloud and John Townsend.

23:56.382 --> 24:02.482
It is like the gold standard for understanding how to love someone without losing yourself or enabling their sin.

24:02.502 --> 24:03.666
I'd recommend you check it out.

24:04.226 --> 24:09.231
We spent some time on this in the previous series as well around some key relationships.

24:09.251 --> 24:19.161
And I talked about my own story of abuse as a child and visited with many of you in person or online as you shared some about what your experience was.

24:19.201 --> 24:20.322
I'm so grateful that you did.

24:20.882 --> 24:26.047
And for many of you, you wanted to know how you could love someone and set boundaries.

24:26.468 --> 24:32.914
And so I wanna make sure before we finish today that you get a tool that maybe can help you do that a little bit more easily

24:33.570 --> 24:36.934
On this tool, we see sort of three different directions.

24:37.094 --> 24:44.663
The first one, most relationships represent this friction space right here, and it's the friction of annoyance.

24:45.044 --> 24:58.480
This is the person that can't close the cabinet doors, that leaves socks on the ground, that for whatever reason, they're just a chaos agent, and they cannot load the dishwasher correctly.

24:59.021 --> 24:59.802
You know what I'm saying?

25:01.203 --> 25:02.525
It's surface level friction.

25:02.545 --> 25:03.346
It's annoying.

25:03.554 --> 25:06.077
It's your spouse choosing to do those things.

25:06.537 --> 25:07.598
That's sandpaper.

25:07.678 --> 25:13.545
It scrapes against our soul, but hopefully you're not gonna leave someone or divorce someone over a dishwasher.

25:14.025 --> 25:16.868
You just aggressively reorganize it after they leave the room.

25:18.050 --> 25:22.354
If someone is sandpaper for us, generally what we give them is grace.

25:22.935 --> 25:30.043
And if you think to yourself, oh my gosh, I can't believe that I have so many people in my life that are sandpaper, you are sandpaper to other people in your life also.

25:31.824 --> 25:33.266
They told me to tell you so.

25:34.786 --> 25:38.272
But hopefully in the midst of that, you recognize that that's not all of it.

25:38.352 --> 25:40.596
The far right is this picture of a sledgehammer.

25:40.936 --> 25:43.260
A sledgehammer is not interested in smoothing you out.

25:43.561 --> 25:46.105
A sledgehammer is interested in breaking you down.

25:46.445 --> 25:47.968
This is abuse.

25:49.070 --> 25:53.798
And with abuse, we don't extend grace in that necessarily.

25:53.918 --> 25:55.300
We just get safe.

25:55.460 --> 25:56.402
We get out of it.

25:56.834 --> 26:02.502
Now, I know that for some of you, that's like a challenge that you feel because you've lived that.

26:02.723 --> 26:06.228
You don't endure a sledgehammer, you run away from a sledgehammer.

26:06.749 --> 26:07.991
But there's a nuance in the middle.

26:08.031 --> 26:11.015
Sometimes we wanna oversimplify and something's either this or this.

26:11.356 --> 26:14.500
I think there's a third option in the middle and that's the scalpel.

26:15.021 --> 26:18.146
See, a scalpel cuts, it causes pain, it draws blood.

26:18.206 --> 26:23.794
But unlike the sledgehammer, the purpose of the scalpel is actually to heal.

26:24.898 --> 26:28.623
See, in the right hands, a scalpel doesn't do damage.

26:28.663 --> 26:29.564
It really helps.

26:29.624 --> 26:32.488
The proverbs of the Hebrew scriptures says it this way.

26:32.548 --> 26:35.052
The wounds of a friend can be trusted.

26:35.072 --> 26:46.908
This is this person that loves you, that can call out your sin, that can challenge your addiction, that can point out the cancer in your character that nobody else can.

26:47.669 --> 26:50.593
So how do you tell the difference between a scalpel and a sledgehammer?

26:51.374 --> 26:54.258
Well, it comes down to permission and seasons.

26:54.626 --> 27:01.254
See, a scalpel, it cuts you open and you only hand a scalpel to a surgeon that you trust.

27:01.274 --> 27:04.938
You never just give a scalpel to anybody, I hope, right?

27:05.879 --> 27:10.145
You have the God-given agency to decide who holds the scalpel in your life.

27:10.185 --> 27:11.486
You give them permission.

27:11.947 --> 27:18.034
You say, I trust your love for me enough to let you hurt my feelings for my good.

27:18.850 --> 27:22.214
In dating, you may never hand the scalpel to someone.

27:22.234 --> 27:28.702
It may all these just be sandpaper because you're sort of trying to show the best of yourselves or surface level friendships or whatever.

27:29.203 --> 27:35.610
You haven't given that scalpel, but in a covenant marriage and a long-term friendship, eventually, you hand them the scalpel.

27:36.431 --> 27:41.037
If someone tries to use a scalpel on you but you haven't given them permission, that's a violation.

27:41.057 --> 27:41.938
You take it back.

27:42.434 --> 27:51.823
And if you've given someone permission in a past season, but they stopped using it to heal and they started using it to hurt, you have the agency to take the scalpel back.

27:52.904 --> 27:54.886
So in short, we endure the sandpaper.

27:55.527 --> 28:03.234
We run from the sledgehammer, but we submit to the scalpel in the hands of someone who loves you, like Jesus loves you, and someone you trust.

28:03.735 --> 28:06.758
And if you go, I just can't find anyone like that anywhere in my life.

28:06.878 --> 28:09.220
It might not be a them problem.

28:09.240 --> 28:11.282
That might be a, there are people in your life

28:11.458 --> 28:16.524
actually probably could speak truth to you that would love you even if it hurts and you've got to choose to trust them.

28:17.445 --> 28:34.606
But let's be honest, if we took that passage we just looked at and we changed it, we took first Corinthians 13 and we just thought, well, what if instead of love is patient, it says like, let's see, fill is patient.

28:34.626 --> 28:37.650
Fill does not envy or boast.

28:37.986 --> 28:39.948
He is not arrogant or rude.

28:40.128 --> 28:42.050
He does not insist on his own way.

28:42.110 --> 28:48.077
He is not irritable or resentful, dot, dot, dot.

28:48.097 --> 28:51.881
Now I just want to say thank you for not laughing as I was writing it.

28:53.522 --> 28:55.945
If my wife was here, she might have, right?

28:55.965 --> 29:04.434
The moment that we swap our names into this passage, we realize that we aren't the foundation, that too often our best attempts

29:04.514 --> 29:05.895
They just look like decoration.

29:06.316 --> 29:11.841
Sure, like we're pretty good when things look good, but we will crack under the weight when things get heavy.

29:11.881 --> 29:21.230
We wanna be the anchor, but we keep acting like the balloon because we're trying to do this on our own, based on our own experiences, based on our own feelings as the foundation.

29:21.951 --> 29:24.514
That's why 1 Corinthians 13 isn't a to-do list.

29:24.614 --> 29:25.575
It's a portrait.

29:25.595 --> 29:30.520
It's a portrait of the only person in history who has lived this out perfectly.

29:30.580 --> 29:33.042
I mean, think about this for a moment.

29:34.082 --> 29:38.427
Take this passage that you've read as love is patient, love is kind, and put Jesus' name in here.

29:39.167 --> 29:40.649
Jesus is patient and kind.

29:41.330 --> 29:43.912
Jesus does not envy or boast.

29:44.293 --> 29:46.075
He is not arrogant or rude.

29:46.415 --> 29:48.197
He does not insist on his own way.

29:48.517 --> 29:51.681
He is not irritable or resentful.

29:51.881 --> 29:55.044
That is actually a portrait of Jesus.

29:55.705 --> 29:56.946
He bears all things.

29:57.006 --> 29:58.087
He believes all things.

29:58.127 --> 29:59.108
He hopes all things.

29:59.148 --> 30:00.690
He endures all things.

30:01.442 --> 30:03.004
Jesus kept no record of wrongs.

30:03.024 --> 30:08.751
As a matter of fact, he took your and my record of wrongs and he nailed it to the cross so that we could be free.

30:08.831 --> 30:16.020
So if you're sitting here feeling guilty because you know that your expression of love has felt kind of flimsy, good.

30:16.080 --> 30:28.316
That guilt is the scalpel of God showing you and me that our pride has gotten in the way so that he can heal us because you cannot generate this kind of love.

30:28.936 --> 30:30.258
You can only reflect it.

30:30.658 --> 30:33.102
You can't fake this kind of foundation.

30:33.202 --> 30:36.647
A real one needs to support the weight of your life.

30:37.649 --> 30:40.313
So here's the practice that I wanna challenge you with this week.

30:41.034 --> 30:48.907
I want you to take off the pressure off of your feelings to try to go, I need my feelings to perfectly match what I know, love, what ask me to do.

30:48.947 --> 30:50.789
Stop asking, do I feel like love today?

30:50.810 --> 30:53.694
And start asking, how do I stand in God's love today?

30:53.734 --> 30:55.897
How do I do this kind of thing?

30:56.138 --> 30:58.802
What would this actually look like in my

30:58.882 --> 31:22.194
life and so just take this line that we've given you for the series and maybe in your phone or on the notes that you're taking right now or in the mirror somewhere in your car just wrote right love is and then the action that God's love is compelling you to take this week maybe for you that action is something as simple as I don't know doing the dishes like the right way you know

31:24.354 --> 31:26.657
Maybe that's listening without interrupting.

31:26.677 --> 31:28.038
Maybe that's putting your phone away.

31:28.299 --> 31:32.824
Maybe it's having a conversation that starts down the path of forgiveness.

31:33.745 --> 31:35.928
What is the first step of love in your life?

31:36.028 --> 31:42.596
Not because it has to generate from your feelings, but because it's the foundation that God has already extended to you.

31:42.616 --> 31:44.478
And listen, I know what some of you are thinking.

31:44.899 --> 31:46.301
You're thinking, Phil, I want this.

31:46.821 --> 31:47.482
I really do.

31:47.562 --> 31:49.024
I want love to be a foundation.

31:49.064 --> 31:51.006
I don't want to be the helium balloon.

31:51.107 --> 31:53.970
I want a love that can handle the scalpel, but I need

31:54.082 --> 31:56.828
help and here's what a lot of you need help with.

31:56.848 --> 32:04.984
You need help to let yourself know for the first time or remember for the first time in a long time what this love is really like.

32:06.387 --> 32:13.522
I mean if you think about it love that is expressed to you and me from God can feel like one of those things we graduate from.

32:13.794 --> 32:20.523
It can feel like one of those things we remember, somebody convinced us of a long time ago, we're grateful for it, but we don't really let ourselves sit in that.

32:20.803 --> 32:26.110
Remember who you are, remember what you've done, remember what you deserve, and remember what God has done.

32:26.691 --> 32:31.457
And so before we're finished today at all of our campuses, we're gonna do a song together called Reckless Love.

32:32.398 --> 32:41.810
And the reason that the song is called Reckless Love is because when you look at the way God loves you and me from our perspective, it looks real reckless.

32:42.306 --> 32:46.933
Like if God had friends that were like him and they were looking at humanity, they'd be like, are you serious?

32:47.153 --> 32:53.543
In first Peter actually, it says that angels look at the way God loves you and me as human beings and they are curious.

32:53.623 --> 32:54.705
They're like, really?

32:55.306 --> 32:57.690
That's the bet we're leaning on that?

32:58.251 --> 33:06.844
And in God's perfect economy, the relationship that he designed, the relationship that he ordained and the future that he has is his love set on you.

33:07.986 --> 33:10.930
You cannot emulate what you have not experienced.

33:12.162 --> 33:16.628
And so over these next few minutes, let this experience wash over you.

33:18.010 --> 33:24.339
Remember the love that the creator of the universe has for you, no matter what you've done or where you've been, even if it's the first time.

33:25.260 --> 33:26.021
Would you pray with me?

33:29.546 --> 33:34.593
God, there are some people in this room right now that I know they just don't think that they deserve love.

33:35.374 --> 33:38.098
There are some people all around the Bay Area that

33:38.338 --> 33:42.104
They think I've gone too far, I've done too much, I've been gone too long.

33:42.685 --> 33:45.128
God must be over it with me.

33:46.210 --> 33:53.681
And God, I know that nothing could be further from the truth, that your love for us is inextinguishable.

33:55.023 --> 33:57.907
But God, would you meet us in this moment?

33:59.089 --> 34:02.033
Would you remind us of the love that you have available?

34:03.155 --> 34:07.762
Would you help us to see that actually, no matter where we've been or what we've done,

34:08.482 --> 34:13.302
You've been here waiting for us with your love forever.

34:14.366 --> 34:17.519
Help us to experience it now in Jesus name.

34:18.845 --> 34:19.186
Amen.

